HTP Chemoproteomics Report

Damon Leach, Kelly Stratton, Lisa Bramer

2023-02-14

Software Used

R 4.2.1 (R Core Team 2018) was used for all computations. The following packages were used:

Package Use Reference
dplyr General data processing Wickham et al. (2018)
ggplot2 Creating figures Wickham (2016)
pmartR Processing/normalizing/analyzing protein data Degnan et al. (2023)

Isobaric Normalization

As the data is labeled, it must undergo isobaric normalization. Figure 1 shows the data before (left) and after (right) undergoing isobaric normalization. Prior to any normalization, there were 6,042 peptides in the data and 5,461 unique peptides. There were also 40,127 missing observations accounting for 66.41% missingness.

Figure 1: Peptide-level data before and after undergoing isobaric normalization

Filters

Before analyses could be ran, the data was filtered. First, the data was subset such that only molecules with a msgf spectral probability value less than 2.7113e-08 were included. After removing peptides with msgf spectral probability values that were too high, there were 1,373 molecules in the data. Peptide redundancies were summed such that we each row corresponded to a single peptide. After this was conducted, unique peptides remaining.

Normalization

Data was then normalized using mean centering. A group specific backtransform was applied on the data . Figure 2 shows the data after undergoing mean centering normalization with a group-specific backtransform .

Figure 2: Peptide-level data after undergoing normalization

Protein Quantitation

Protein quantitation on the data using the “rollup” method placing the data on the protein-level rather than peptide-level. After undergoing protein quantitation, there were 762 unique proteins in the data. There were 5,292 missing observations accounting for 77.17% missingness.

Reverse Hits/Contaminants

Reverse hits and contaminants that remained in the data were removed. After removing those molecules, there were 436 unique proteins in the data. There were 2,607 missing observations accounting for 66.44% missingness. Figure 3 shows the normalized protein-level data after quantitation and removal of reverse hits and contaminants.

Figure 3: Protein-level data after undergoing quantitation and removal of reverse hits and contaminants

Results

We can look at the number of significant fold changes between all comparisons. Figure 4 demonstrates the number of significant fold changes by each pairwise comparison in both a bar plot and a volcano plot.

Figure 4: Significant fold changes by both bar plot (left) and volcano plot (right)

Statistical results for each protein are given in the file ‘results_job_2,044,576.csv’ . Within this csv, there are the following columns:

Column Name Description
Protein Protein identifier
Count_X Number of counts for Group X
Mean_X Mean value for Group X
Fold_change_X_vs_Y log2 fold-change of viral strain X/Y
P_value_A_X_vs_Y Adjusted p-value for comparison of X and Y
Flag_A_X_vs_Y Flag for comparison of X and Y condition
